dataIdInfo.idPurp: The purpose of these vector datasets is to provide atlas block boundaries for the second Wisconsin Breeding Bird Atlas (WBBA II). These files also document the atlas block boundaries for the first WBBA and replace files generated in 1995.
dataIdInfo.idAbs:
These datasets were created in preparation for the 2015 Wisconsin Breeding Bird Atlas (WBBA II). The USGS 1:24K Index quad layer was used as the starting point to generate all locational data in these datasets. All features were generated using ArcGIS/arcpy.

WBBA blocks were formed by dividing 1:24K quads in half in the east-west dimension and in thirds in the north-south dimension. Block and point feature classes were derived from the USGS 1:24K Index using "CreateFishnet_management".

Percent water and percent land were calculated using "TabulateIntersection_analysis" after projecting input data sources to USA_Contiguous_Albers_Equal_Area_Conic (WKID 102003). The union of the 2013 US Census TIGER/Line county shapefile and WDNR Wisconsin State boundary was used to estimate percent WI (political boundary) per block. NHD waterbody was used to estimate percent water per block.

This version (v0.2) adds specialty blocks for WBBA II, and 6-letter codes to identify blocks on GPS units.

This collection is made up of four vector datasets:

WbbaBlockLabels2015_v0_2.shp: Point feature class containing the centroid of each WBBA II block

WbbaBlocks2015_v0_2.shp: Polygon feature class containing all WBBA II blocks (2015)

WbbaBlocks1995_v0_2.shp: Polygon feature class containing all WBBA I blocks (replaces blocks produced in 1995)

WbbaQuadIndex2015_v0_2.shp: Polygon feature class contain all USGS 1:24K Index quads used to derive the WBBA blocks in this collection

The script used to generate these features was "GenerateWbbaBlocksFishnet.py" (last updated 21 Feb 2015).

Data sources used to generate the 2015 WBBA blocks and supporting datasets:

USGS 1:24K Index quads ("TNM_Cells.gdb/Cells/CellGrid_7_5Minute") were downloaded from <ftp://nhdftp.usgs.gov/DataSets/Staged/Cells/> [accessed 17 Oct 2013]. Metadata is available from <http://services.nationalmap.gov/ArcGIS/rest/services/selectable_polygons/MapServer>.

The 2013 US Census TIGER/Line county shapefile ("tl_2013_us_county.shp") was downloaded from <ftp://ftp2.census.gov/geo/tiger/TIGER2013/COUNTY/> [accessed 7 Aug 2014]. Metadata ("TGRSHP2013_TechDoc") is available from <https://www.census.gov/geo/maps-data/data/pdfs/tiger/tgrshp2013/TGRSHP2013_TechDoc.pdf>.

Wisconsin Department of Natural Resources (WDNR) Wisconsin State boundary ("WI_state_outline.shp") was downloaded from <ftp://dnrftp01.wi.gov/geodata/WI_state_outline/> [accessed 20 Aug 2014]. Metadata "WI_state_outline.pdf" available at <http://dnr.wi.gov/maps/gis/documents/WI_state_outline.pdf>).

National Hydrography Dataset'(NHD) waterbody dataset ("NHDH_WI.gdb/Hydrography/NHDWaterbody"; "NHDH_WI_931v210.zip"; Data Model 2.1) was downloaded from <ftp://nhdftp.usgs.gov/DataSets/Staged/States/FileGDB/HighResolution/> [accessed 26 Sept 2012].

Block status for WBBA II (2015). Blocks can have a status of "Priority", "Specialty", or "Regular".
From the WBBA II handbook:
Priority Blocks
The ultimate ideal for an atlas would be to survey all 6 blocks in each quad. But with Wisconsin's large size, the time limit for surveying, and the distribution and number of observers, this is not possible. Since equivalent coverage throughout the state is critical, as with the first atlas, we designated the centereast Block (CE) of each quad as the priority block. This block in all quads (unless CE contains limited WI land) must be adequately surveyed in order for the atlas to be complete. To illustrate, it is preferable for only 1 block to be surveyed in every quad in the state than for all 6 blocks to be surveyed in 80% of the state while 20% of the quads are left unsurveyed. County Coordinators are responsible for assuring that the priority blocks in their areas are surveyed. Habitat codes are recommended but not required when atlasing in priority blocks.
Specialty Blocks
In addition to the priority blocks, other blocks have been selected for special attention and will be surveyed. These specialty blocks represent sites of unique habitat or particular ornithological interest. For WBBA II, we primarily selected specialty blocks that represented high-quality examples of the following high-priority habitat types that might not otherwise receive good coverage: bottomland hardwoods, coastal and islands, conifer swamp, emergent marsh, grassland, pine barrens, southern forest interior, upland shrubs, and wet meadow. We also considered whether a block was a specialty block during the first atlas (we retained many, but not all of these, and some blocks that were intended to be specialty during the first atlas did not get coverage). County Coordinators are responsible for assuring that the specialty blocks in their areas are surveyed. Habitat codes are required when atlasing in specialty blocks.
Regular Blocks
While the importance of getting priority and specialty blocks completed cannot be overemphasized, there is no restriction from working in the other blocks. In fact, surveys in regular blocks are welcomed, but not at the expense of priority and specialty blocks. For example, if your residence or cabin is not in a priority block, you could survey in the nearest priority block as well as in the block that contains your property. Incidental reports from regular blocks can provide important information on areas that might not otherwise get coverage. (Note: these were termed “supplemental blocks” during the first atlas). Habitat codes are recommended but not required when atlasing in regular blocks.

attr.attrdef: Priority blocks from the 1995 WBBA. No more than one priority block per quad.

Unique identifier for each block to be used on GPS units. Waypoint codes were generated using rules roughly based on bird alpha codes. Each code consists of 4 letters taken from a quad name (QUAD_NAME) followed by the 2 letters indicating the location of the block within the quad (BLOCK_POS). Dashes were treated the same as spaces when counting the number of words in a name.
Basic rules: * One word quad name: use the first 4 letters of the quad name * Two word name: use the first 2 letters of each word * Three word name: use the first letter of the first 2 words, and the first 2 letters of the last word * Four word name: use the first letter of each word * Five word name: use the first letter of the first 2 words, and the first 2 letters of the last word
The five word rule was chosen because the only 5 word names were Jump River Fire Tower NE, NW, and SW. This allowed the direction to be retained.
There were no names with more than 5 words. One quad name contained parentheses, but as the rules state, only letters were used [e.g., "Green Bay (All Water) – SW" was assigned "GBAWSW" and not "GB(WSW"].
Three quad names ("Ino" "Nye" "Rio") were less than 4 letters long. Underscores were used in these cases to pad the names to four characters. For example "Ino - CE" was assigned "INO_CE".
Conflicting codes were corrected by hand. Generally, the last assigned letter from a word was substituted for the last letter in the word with preference given to substituting from the first word. For example, "Balsam Lake" and "Barker Lake" both result in "BALA". To correct this, "Balsam Lake" was assigned "BMLA" and "Barker Lake" retained "BALA". In cases were substituting a letter in this way for one or more words did not fix all conflicts, the second to last letter was used instead. Using this strategy allowed for unique codes to be created for all blocks.
The source file for this attribute was "WayptCodes20150113.csv".

attrdomv.udom: Unique combination of 6 capital letters. The first 4 letters are based on the quad name (QUAD_NAME); the last 2 letters indicate the position within the block (BLOCK_POS).

attr.attrdef: Wisconsin county at centroid of block based on 2013 US Census TIGER/Line county shapefile. County was assigned by hand for blocks with centroids that did not fall in a WI county.
